rsinia pestis","Pneumocystis jirovecii"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EYersinia pestis\u003C/strong\u003E is a gram-negative coccobacillus known for causing plague. It is a facultative intracellular bacterium, meaning it can survive both inside and outside host cells. This ability allows it to evade the host\u0027s immune system and is a key factor in its pathogenicity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECandida albicans\u003C/strong\u003E is a yeast, not a bacterium, and is not classified as intracellular. It is a common cause of fungal infections in humans.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECryptococcus neoformans\u003C/strong\u003E is a yeast-like fungus that can cause severe infections, particularly in immunocompromised individuals. It is not a bacterium and does not have intracellular capabilities.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspergillus fumigatus\u003C/strong\u003E is a mold that can cause respiratory infections, especially in individuals with weakened immune systems. It is not a bacterium and does not exhibit intracellular behavior.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPneumocystis jirovecii\u003C/strong\u003E is a fungus that causes pneumonia in immunocompromised patients. It is not a bacterium and does not have intracellular characteristics.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Facultative intracellular bacteria can survive and replicate both inside and outside host cells.","Yersinia pestis is a gram-negative coccobacillus that causes plague and is a facultative intracellular bacterium.","Fungi like Candida, Cryptococcus, Aspergillus and Pneumocystis are not classified as intracellular organisms."],"references":["Sastry, A. S., \u0026 Bhat, S. (2018). Essentials of medical microbiology. JP Medical Ltd","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u00